-*- How do I put two columns in a combo box and show only one of the
columns to the user?

This comes in very handy when you want to hide your key field from the
user. For example a database containing people's phone numbers and
addresses would have a field [PersonsID] and [LastName]; if the user
is to select a person from the list you want to present a combo box
full of last names, but you want the value of the combo box to be a
[PersonsID]. Set the combo box columns property to 2, and set the
column widths property to: 0 in; 2 in, finally set the bound column
property to 1. 

-*- How do I get a correct count of the number of records in a
recordset?

First you must check the recordset's EOF property to see if it is an
empty recordset. If EOF is true right after you open it, the recordset
it empty. (BOF will also be set to true).

Once you know that the recordset contains records, you must move to
the last record in the recordset before checking the recordset's
RecordCount property, like this:

        Dim db As Database, rs As Recordset, numRecs As Integer
        db = DBEngine.Workspaces(0).Databases(0)
        rs = db.OpenRecordset("QrySomeQuery")
        If rs.EOF Then
           MsgBox "This recordset is empty"
        Else
           rs.movelast
           numRecs = rs.recordcount
           MsgBox "Number of records is " & str(numRecs)
        End If


-*- What are some books about Access?


"Using Access 2 for Windows", Roger Jennings, Que Corp., 1994, 1218
pages, $29.99 US.

This is a very good book, both as a reference and as an
introduction. It has a large section on producing an Access
application, with all the details and fine touches you want. All the
database functions are well covered, except Access Basic, in which
this book, like every other Access book I have seen, is weak. This
book does have the best Access Basic coverage I have seen, but it's
still not that good.


"Running Microsoft Access 2 for Windows", John Viescas, Microsoft
Press,1994, 900 pages, $39.95 US. Disk included.

This book is a good intro and has a strong intro and reference section
about SQL. Access Basic is poorly covered. Advanced topics are not
well covered. The included disk contains a sample application that
seems to be little improvement on those already included with
Access. I think this book is a bit overpriced.

"Access 2 Developers Guide", Roger Jennings, SAMS Publishing. Disk
included. 

This is the next book I'll by. It has gotten rave reviews from all
posters who mentioned it, and is rumored to be strong in the Access
Basic area.

"The Access Bible", Cary Prague

"Teach Yourself Access 2.0 in 14 Days", SAMS Publishing.

Supposed to be a great intro and a great way to learn Access, but not
too strong as a technical reference.


